# <a id="_li5rwgcve8r"></a>Competitor Product Portfolio Overviews

## <a id="_l1yyxe24hshr"></a>UserTesting

The UserTesting portfolio has four major components:

### <a id="_o1nw6nrfuy7i"></a>Human Insight Platform

The Human Insight Platform is UserZoom’s core product\. It consists of 

- __CxN Audience Management __which includes features for Audience recruitment, profile management, Incentive payments, quality control, onboarding and support, and Security and privacy\.
- __Customer Experience Narrative \(CxN\) Core __which includes features for Live interviews, Usability testing, Brand and messaging testing, Card sorting, Tree testing, and Clickstream tracking
- __Human Insight Management__ which includes features for Data visualization, Auto\-generated analytics, and transcriptions, IIntelligent insights, Folders and workspaces, Highlight reels and results download and sharing links
- __Data And Machine Learning__ which includes features for Interactive Path Flows, Sentiment and Intent Path, Instant Insight, Keyword mapping, Click maps, and Audience QA and performance management

### <a id="_7vypg0v8ri2h"></a>UserZoom

The complete UserZoom product portfolio is described below\.

### <a id="_x178idh9nec3"></a>EnjoyHQ

EnjoyHQ solution that enables teams to centralize and share insights from customer research to amplify the value and impact across their organization\.

### <a id="_mnru1tpy6kw9"></a>Research Services

Research Services__ __include strategy and consulting, full\-service research, Benchmark experiences with QXscore™, audience services, and accessibility testing\. 

## <a id="_i3vkuwq6t366"></a>UserZoom

UserZoom is positioned as a secondary product for UserTesting\. As an account executive described in a discovery call

‘’So we have technically we have two products, right? But the majority of folks that have conversations with us are turning to user testing, right? Core product because that's essentially going to solve the majority of their needs\. It's only if you're looking to do kind of more highly, you know, statistically relevant, you know, we also have offerings from our acquired organization\. \[UserZoom\]’’

UserZoom has four major components in its portfolio:

- __Research Platform__\. The research platform has features for recruitment, Live interviews, Usability testing, Card sorting, Surveys, Click testing, Mixed\-method studies, and Benchmarking with QXscore
- __Participant recruitment__ includes features for Demographic filters, Customizable screeners, Audience segments, Automated session scheduling, and Automated incentive distribution 
- __EnjoyHQ Insights Hub__ is the UserTesting solution that enables teams to centralize and share insights from customer research to amplify the value and impact across their organization\.\. It includes features for storing and managing customer research data in one central location, collaborations, integrations with third\-party tools, and automated insights like automatic transcription, advanced search, tagging, and filtering\.
- __Research Services __including strategy and consulting, full\-service research, benchmark experiences with QXscore™, audience services, and accessibility testing 

## <a id="_ckmbfpucgiif"></a>dscout

The dscout platform has four major components:

### <a id="_jdky9zelila"></a>Recruit

Recruit allows a customer to recruit participants for ‘missions’\. Recruit enables a user to define a screening test that can include demographic requirements, answers to multiple choice or open\-ended questions, and video submissions, Users can recruit from dscout’s 100,000\+ panel that represents all US states, metropolitan areas, income brackets, ethnicities, gender identities, household compositions, and age ranges\. Recruit supports inviting people that are not part of the dscout panel to participate in ‘missions’\. Recruit has machine language\-powered tools to help identify the best candidates for a ‘mission’\.

### <a id="_w70eym9oe66j"></a>Diary

Diary is dscout’s unmoderated research solution\. Users can design ‘missions’ that include prototype feedback, competitive analysis, in\-the\-wild product discovery, fieldwork supplementations, shopalongs, etc\. Missions can include multiple choice and open\-ended question responses, screen captures, video commentary by participants, etc\. Missions can be a single session or be spread out over multiple days\.

### <a id="_11plqzv51phl"></a>Live

Live is dscout’s moderated research solution\. It enables one\-on\-one interviews and recording,, inviting observers, taking notes, and sharing screens without toggling through tabs\. The tool provides full transcription\.

### <a id="_1ot1exmtu9kh"></a>Express

Express is a simplified version of the Diary product that focuses on rapidly executing ‘missions’ using only participants in the discount 100,000 participant panel\.

## <a id="_p2xid2opulhl"></a>Suzy

The Suzy portfolio has five components:

### <a id="_musacjmualzv"></a>Suzy Insights

Insights is Suzy’s unmoderated research solution\.  The primary features include survey design, heat mapping, video open ends, tester targeting, and retargeting\. Suzy offers unique capabilities for Monadic Testing, MaxDiff Analysis, Conjoint Analysis, and TURF Analysis

### <a id="_ncqvb8cfx3ul"></a>Suzy Live

Live is Suzy’s moderated testing solution\. The primary features include scheduling and logistics, bookmarking and clipping, tester targeting and retargeting, and showreels\.

### <a id="_6ycfko8pumw7"></a>Suzy Audiences

Suzy Audiences is Suzy’s testing panel management solution\. The primary features include screening and verification, quotas & demographics, USA and International participants, dynamic segmentation, and biotic actions\.

### <a id="_14f4lpzf917r"></a>Suzy In\-Home Usage Testing \(iHUT\)

Suzy In\-Home Usage Testing \(iHUT\) is a managed service offered by Suzy\. They describe it as “Tell us about your product, screening criteria, and test objectives\. We will work together to create a test plan\. Then, send your product to our fulfillment center, and we’ll take care of the rest \- finding a qualified audience and ensuring that they receive your products\. You can gather feedback via Suzy and Suzy Live… or have our Managed Services do it for you\.

### <a id="_ku3tqwamv59"></a>Suzy Dynamic Market Segmentation

Suzy Dynamic Market Segmentation is a managed service for building testing panels that meet a customer’s unique requirements\. It includes:

- Cluster analysis details with segment definitions, buyer personas, predictive product and brand perception attributes and a custom typing tool  
- Actionable segments added to your Suzy dashboard
- 3 custom templates for product ideas/concepts, packaging, and campaign  assets \-\- in your Suzy dashboard
- 3 quarterly segment refreshes to keep your segments up to date

## <a id="_6kf2ndxz8qho"></a>Maze

Maze is a platform for unmoderated research\. It does not support moderated research\. The core platform has four major feature groups:

- __Build__\. Design a ‘mission’\. A mission is a sequence of blocks\. Blocks can be open and closed end questions, multiple choice, card sorts, tree tests, or video clips to capture a tester’s audio and video during a mission\.
- __Share__\. The features that enable a user to invite participants to a mission\. Maze supports multiple methods for invites\. Maze also offers a panel of 127,000\+ powered by Prolific\. T[here are several limitations](https://help.maze.co/hc/en-us/articles/360051963254#01G0478F7GR455N5CXBGK0SY65) regarding what a Prolific panel member can do versus a user\-invited tester can do\.
- __Results__\. Features that present test results\.
- __Report__\. Features that enable mission results to be shared across the organization and via integrations to tools like Figma, Adobe XB, and InVision

Manager, Web Experience | Marketing & Brand Management Office

Small\-Business\(50 or fewer emp\.\)

Validated Reviewer

Incentivized Review

Mar 20, 2023

"Simple UI for any team member to launch, analyze & report out on user\-tests\!"

What do you like best about UserTesting?

The user interface makes the complex task of setting up, launching, reviewing and sharing findings out, easy to navigate and easy to look back on past tests\. My department will often run reoccuring user\-tests for things such as our website homepage, our top conversions on our website, etc\., being able to repeat tests and use previous test plans was super helpful\. The ability to share a single video clip or a highlight reel was also extremely helpful in sharing takeaways across a multidisciplinary team, as well as with stakeholders\.

What do you dislike about UserTesting?

The cost of using UserTesting\.com as our enterprise platform seemed steep in comparison to similar products\. We also seemed to constantly be given a new "account manager" or "personal rep" for UserTesting\.com, which was annoying for the team to have to do kickoff calls with this new position every so often\.

Review collected by and hosted on G2\.com\.

What problems is UserTesting solving and how is that benefiting you?

The qualitative feedback that we can't get through just analytics or survey and in\-person feedback from a limited audience\. Having a giant user pool like UserTesting,com has is super helpful in testing products across multiple audiences, especially with how fast the feedback can be delivered back to your team\. This has been most useful for website redesigns, where we can launch a baseline user\-test, test the prototype, and then test post\-launch\.

The synthesis tools are good for looking at research holistically across clicks and replies\. I also appreciate watching videos and the ease of creating, sharing, and stringing together video clips\.

What do you dislike about UserTesting?

The program is slow, and the menu options are hard to find\. It takes a few times to remember all the settings and how to adjust them\. It's also difficult to copy data out of the tool if you need to access it later\.

I like that I have the option to use my own panel, but their panel is very well trained\. I've found the feedback from their trained users to be slightly biased due to their testing experience\.

Users also struggle to move the controls out of the way during testing and remember to see the prompt\. They really struggle with the interface, and it can bias results\. The old interface was a bit smoother for users\.

What problems is UserTesting solving and how is that benefiting you?

Usability and click testing\. It can be nice to have a consistently test that I don't need to modify\.

## <a id="_rtt281a6qzt5"></a>UserTesting

UserTesting does not disclose pricing information publicly\. UserTesting pricing appears to be a combination of

1. Feature Packages \(Essentials, Advanced, Ultimate\)
2. Number of Researcher Users
3. Number of Tests run every year

On their website, they disclose three pricing plans:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

[https://www\.usertesting\.com/plans](https://www.usertesting.com/plans) 

In discussions with a UserTesting account executive he noted “In a nutshell, if you're familiar with purchasing like AWS services, a very similar consumption model, it's generally how we run things as well here\.\. \. \. off of those two things that I mentioned is going to be what's your consumption going to look like for the year and then, you know, how many people in your society are going to be running through that consumption\.

According to [UserTesting’s last 10\-Q they filed in August 2022](https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1557127/000155712722000039/user-20220331.htm) “The terms of the Company’s subscription agreements are primarily annual and, to a lesser extent, multi\-year\. The Company's subscription agreements are generally non\-cancellable\.”

In August 2022 UserTesting had $97\.4M of deferred revenue on its balance sheet\. For Q2 2022, UserTesting reported $45\.8M in total Q2 revenue\.

# <a id="_9vih5jhc4wkt"></a>SWOT Analysis

## <a id="_31seknepf77r"></a>UserTesting

- Strengths
	- Market dominance\. Annual revenues are 5X nearest competitor
	- Backing of Thoma Bravo
	- Most comprehensive and advanced product portfolio
	- Enjoy HQ product provides industry\-leading integrations to tools like Salesforce, Zendesk, Slack, Jira, Trello, and Zoom
	- Sophisticated analytical capabilities that are unmatched by competition
	- Largest global employee footprint of all competitors in market
- Weaknesses
	- Perception that UserTesting has the highest total cost of ownership
	- Price points and commercial terms \(prepaid non\-cancellable contracts\) are a barrier to midmarket and SMB adoption
	- Lack of clarity in the long term roadmap for UserZoom products\. Will they be fully integrated into the Human Insight Platform or remain as standalone offerings?
- Opportunities
	- More international expansion, especially in the EU and Asia Pacific
	- Clarification of the long\-term UserZoom roadmap
	- Repackaging of offerings to offer a lower price point for midmarket and SMB prospects
- Threats
	- The rise of Tier II competitors \(Suzy, Maze, and dscout\) that combined have raised almost $100M in VC funding in the past two years
	- The impact of decelerating revenue growth\. The last quarter that UserTesting was public before being taken private b Thoma Bravo showed a material decline in revenue growth rates
	- Potential morale/cultural integration issues from UserTesting ‘acquiring’ UserZoom since Thoma Bravo acquired UserZoom first and then acquired UserTesting seven months later, UserTesting’s CEO became the CEO of the combined entity
	- Potential distraction if Thoma Bravo exits UserTesting via IPO or strategic acquisition\. Average holding time for homa Bravo investments is 4\.8 years

## <a id="_qgzt91jdb3b"></a>UserZoom

- Strengths
	- Market recognition of strength as a platform for high participant volume moderated and unmoderated research
	- Global scale of participant panel \- 120M vs 1\.6M for UserTesting vs 100K for dscout
	- Analytic features like click paths and heatmaps
	- Proprietary QXScore and benchmarks
	- Ability to leverage EnjoyHQ for integrations to third\-party tools
- Weaknesses
	- Perception that UserZoom is primarily focused on high volume studies that require, statistically significant results
	- Lack of clarity in the long term roadmap for UserZoom products\. Will they be fully integrated into the Human Insight Platform or remain as standalone offerings
	- The necessity to purchase enterprise\-level subscriptions to access valuable advanced features
- Opportunities
	- More international expansion, especially in the EU and Asia Pacific
	- Clarification of the long\-term UserZoom roadmap
	- Repackaging of offerings to offer a lower price point for midmarket and SMB prospects
- Threats
	- The rise of Tier II competitors \(Suzy, Maze, and dscout\) that combined have raised almost $100M in VC funding in the past two years
	- Potential morale/cultural integration issues from UserTesting ‘acquiring’ UserZoom since Thoma Bravo acquired UserZoom first and then acquired UserTesting seven months later
	- Potential distraction if Thoma Bravo exits UserTesting via IPO or strategic acquisition\. Average holding time for homa Bravo investments is 4\.8 years

## <a id="_bm8y42ogsixm"></a>dscout 

- Strengths
	- Perception that solution is purpose\-built to improve the productivity of UX researchers
	- Perception that dscout suite has highest ease of use in the market
	- The depth and quality of professional services that maximize customer success
- Weaknesses
	- The lack or relative immaturity of click path tracking, heatmaps, and sentiment analysis
	- Lack of integrations like UserTesting and UserZoom support
	- The perception that dscout professional services are required to ensure successful use of platform
	- Limited international presence
	- Ability to execute\. 203 employees versus UserTesting’s 1,671 employees
- Opportunities
	- More international expansion, especially in the EU and Asia Pacific
	- More analytic features like click path tracking, heatmaps, and sentiment analysis
	- More integrations like those provided by EnjoyHQ
- Threats
	- The rise of Tier II competitors well\-funded competitors like Suzy and Maze
	- The inability to deliver market parity features to successfully compete with UserTesting
	- The need to raise a Series D in late 2023 or 2024

## <a id="_4abk29ovr4o9"></a>Suzy

- Strengths
	- Most comprehensive portfolio of solutions for consumer\-oriented user research
	- Superior tester sourcing and qualification
	- Appears to have the most sophisticated features for survey design, heat mapping, video open ends, tester targeting, and retargeting\. 
	- Unique capabilities for Monadic Testing, MaxDiff Analysis, Conjoint Analysis, TURF Analysis
	- Unique set of managed services offerings unmatched by competition
	- Unique In\-Home User Testing \(iHut\) solution for consumer goods
	- $104M in total funding, including a $50M Series D led by H\.I\.G\. Capital in 2021
- Weaknesses
	- Suzy’s ability to execute on a global basis is constrained by its headcount of 296 versus UserTesting’s 1,671
	- Suzy’s almost exclusive focus on consumer\-centric research limits its ability to tackle B2B user research
	- The total lack of publicly available price information may impact Suzy’s web\-based demand generation efforts\.
- Opportunities
	- Suzy could expand its geographic footprint to include the EU and Asia Pacific
- Threats
	- Suzy’s greatest strength is its focus on consumer\-centric research\. UserTesting has access to the capital required for it to pivot in Suzy’s direction\.
	- Potential disruption/distraction if H\.I\.G decides to exit its investment by IPO or strategic acquisition

## <a id="_m9ya1ft4lhsf"></a>Maze

- Strengths
	- Maze has two primary focuses on unmoderated testing of 1\) user testing of live websites and 2\) testing of designs created in tools like Figma, Adobe XD, and InVision
	- In spite of being founded in 2018, Maze has grown to over $40M in revenue\. An impressive achievement with its limited product footprint\.
	- Maze’s requirement to embed code in live websites encourages vendor lock\-in\.
- Weaknesses
	- No moderated testing capabilities
	- Significantly inferior features for tester screening, video marking, etc,
	- No mechanism for payments to testing participant incentives
	- No automatic transcript generation
	- No sentiment or other advanced analytic capabilities 
	- Limitations of Prolific sourced testing panels
	- No ISO 27001 certification
- Opportunities
	- Expand product functionality in recruitment, participant scheduling and logistics, study design, and analytics
	- Either resolve limitations of Prolific panels or build Maze\-controlled panels like UserTesting, dscout, and Suzy
- Threats
	- Lack of product functionality and testing panels could hinder long term revenue growth
	- The potential need to raise a Series C in 2024
	- Disruption to operations if investors decide to exit
